Name><gtr:otherNames>Mary</gtr:otherNames><gtr:surname>Macpherson</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FE016413%2F1"><gtr:id>F548E3D8-DD11-492D-B4A0-BAFAD159D865</gtr:id><gtr:title>Landscapes of sight and blindness: access, touch and memory in the English Countryside</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/E016413/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>This research investigates people with blindness and visual impairments experiences of walking in the English Countryside. The research focuses on visitors to the Lake District and Peak District who walk in groups with sighted guides. The research ties into the ESRC?s key research areas ?life course, lifestyles and health? and ?social stability and exclusion?. &lt;/p> 
&lt;p>The rationale for this research is threefold:&lt;/p> 
&lt;ul> 
 &lt;li>Firstly, there is very little academic research which investigates and represents the leisure experiences of disabled people in the countryside yet this is an area of contemporary policy and academic relevance&lt;br />&lt;/li> 
 &lt;li>Secondly, a visual, scenic conception of the English landscape is found to dominate popular, academic and policy imaginaries, however, the presence of blind and visually impaired people in the landscape force this visual concept to be questioned&lt;br />&lt;/li> 
 &lt;li>Thirdly, social scientists have often tended to rely on traditional interview and survey formats. This research advances methodological theory and practice by exploring how to research, write and represent differing embodied experiences in the countryside through a range of methods and representational strategies including; in-depth ethnography, interviews, video, photographic material and the use of paintings by people who are blind and visually impaired.&lt;/li>
&lt;/ul></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2008-07-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2007-05-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>89001</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications/><gtr:identifiers><gtr:identifier type="RCUK">ES/E016413/1</gtr:identifier></gtr:identifiers><gtr:healthCategories/><gtr:researchActivities/><gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>B57EEFB7-602E-4F5D-92E4-A0C265266249</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Demography &amp; human geography</gtr:text></gtr:researchSubject><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>E844174D-6A1C-4D2D-8F24-57698F7DA353</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Environmental planning</gtr:text></gtr:researchSubject><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>F0322ED6-113F-4530-BA5E-562216587E68</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Sociology</gtr:text></gtr:researchSubject></gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchTopics><gtr:researchTopic><gtr:id>E844174D-6A1C-4D2D-8F24-57698F7DA353</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Environmental planning</gtr:text></gtr:researchTopic><gtr:researchTopic><gtr:id>3A4CB57C-9B22-41A2-AB15-127503299365</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Human Geography</gtr:text></gtr:researchTopic><gtr:researchTopic><gtr:id>F0322ED6-113F-4530-BA5E-562216587E68</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Sociol